snippet.textDisplay:
Can't stand the taste of butter. I prefer to coat the steaks with olive oil, then season them... then put them into a dry hot pan fat side down and render the beef fat into the pan. Once the fat has darkened then flip it onto its side and cook it in its own fat and it gives the steak an intense meaty flavour, far superior to butter.

I tend to cut my steak too thinly though but that's just because I don't have a lot of money, so cutting it thinly and bulking it out with veg and carbs allows me to feed the family and everyone gets a bit of protein.

snippet.textDisplay:
The average serving of steak is 3 ounces (85.049g)
You have 12.2 million subscribers
If each go out to make a steak, presuming they only make one for themselves and dont have family or friends to cook for, being conservative, a total of 1037597800 grams or 1037.5978 tons of beef. Lets just round it to .6
The average weight of the carcass harvested from beef cattle cow is 476kg
You would need 2178 and a half cows (presuming all of the meat harvested is a steak cut, once again being conservative)
to produce one pound of beef is 1,799 gallons of water
1pound to kg is 0.454 1799gallons x .454 = 816.746 gallons to litre is 3091.72
Wait get this. Thats .454kg of beef requires 3091.72 now multiply that by 1037.6 tons
7061928403.15 litres of water is required to raise the beef cattle to feed your subscribers a 3 ounce steak.
7061928.40315 cubic meters = to tons
According to a government pdf on area required to raise your cattle you need around 2 acres per animal.
You need 17.628 square kilometers to raise your cattle.
https://www.google.com/url?sa=t&source=web&rct=j&url=https://www.nrcs.usda.gov/Internet/FSE_DOCUMENTS/stelprdb1167344.pdf&ved=2ahUKEwiA2PvCv8bmAhWPyDgGHf8ICrEQFjABegQIDBAG&usg=AOvVaw0w9_gGtsjOfPVnoVrW56Xx

snippet.textDisplay:
other important things people always get wrong
-- don't put a cold ass steak into a pan. it fucks so many things up.
-- don't use shitty oil like vegetable, crisco, canola blends, or overly fancy crap like extra virgin.

-- don't burn / smoke the oil. you'll know you fucked up when the pan / oil smells bitter and unappetizing
-- don't use a thin ass flimsy weightless pan. it doesn't get hot enough, and it can't stay hot
-- if there isn't a loud, consistent sizzle the whole time you're searing the steak, you fucked up
-- if most of the surface area of the steak is gray instead of brown, you fucked up
-- if most of the inside of the steak is gray, you fucked up
-- don't eat it if you fucked up

snippet.textDisplay: I can never get the sear right.  I know my pan is hot enough because I use cast iron and a high smoke point oil but I think my steak is never as dry as what's shown in these videos. Even after i pat it down with paper towel, it still looks slightly wet. I think all the steaks used in these vids have been dry aged prior to cooking which is why they can sear so well.
